    "# Initial Imports"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,

   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from hoki import load\n",
    "from time import time\n",
    "import gc\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.style.use('./tuto.mplstyle')"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Introduction\n",
    "\n",
    "The BPASS outputs contain a lot of information that is pretty much ready for analysis and can be quickly loaded through `hoki` (e.g. HR Diagrams, star counts etc...) \n",
    "\n",
    "But if you're looking to match your observation to specific stellar models present in BPASS, say a binary system with primary ZAMS 9 $M_{\\odot}$ and absolute F814w magnitude = X, then you will need to explore the large library of BPASS stellar models to get those evolution tracks.\n",
    "\n",
    "The best way to go about that is to compile all the relevant data (i.e. the IMFs and metallicities you want, for single or binary models) into one or multiple DataFrames that can then be saved into binary files.\n",
    "**Loading data from binary files is much faster** and it means you won't have to compile your data frome text files multiple times. \n",
    "In this tutorial we will use pre-compiled DataFrames - if you want to learn how to make your own (but you probably won't need to), check the `ModelDataCompiler` tutorial.\n",
    "\n",
    "###  Downloading pre-compiled DataFrames\n",
    "\n",
    "I have already compiled all of the BPASS stellar models for the fiducial IMF (Kroupa 1.35 maximum mass = 300 solar masses) into 26 DataFrames (one for each fo the 13 metallicities times 2 for the binay and single star models). \n",
    "\n",
    "You can find the full data set [**here**](https://zenodo.org/record/4064300#.X3fm63VfhNw) (just download what you need).\n",
    "\n",
    "# Model Search\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we'll demonstrate how to find BPASS models that match a simple set of observational data. We are using two HST magnitudes: F435W=-7.33, F814W=-8.46.\n",
    "\n",
    "We'll crop the data step by step and give a few tips and tricks along the way. \n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "### Loading the Data\n",
    "\n",
    "For this particular exercise we are interested in a \"SN\" progenitor in a binary system - we assume solar metallicity, but if you have Z information, use whatever is closest.  \n",
    "\n",
    "**Note:** The required pickle file is NOT included in the tutorial repository because it's too large. You'll have to download it yourself."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",

   "cell_type": "markdown",

   "source": [
    "That's 2,503,198 rows and 100 columns.\n",
    "\n",
    "Note that there **aren't** 2.5 million models:  Each model has between 100 and 400 rows (roughly) that contain the time evolution of each column. It's still a lot of models though, but about 2 orders of magnitude fewer than the number of rows. \n",
    "\n",
    "# Chopping off the bulk of models we don't need\n",
    "\n",
    "Before we match our magnitudes, there are a lot of models that are irrelevant to what we are doing that we can get rid of right off the bat. \n",
    "\n",
    "### Binaries only \n",
    "Something important to note is that the BPASS binary models **contain single stars**. Binaries are important, but they are introduced in a proportion similar to what has been observationally determined (see the BPASS manual for more information or just go to Moe and Die Stefano 2017). \n",
    "\n",
    "Since we only care about the binary star models, we can remove most of the 5 `types` - chekc the manual for full descriptions but here is a wuick reminder:\n",
    "- -1: Signle\n",
    "- 0: Merger before MS\n",
    "- 1: Normal Primary\n",
    "- 2: Normal Secondary\n",
    "- 3: Single Secondary\n",
    "- 4: QHE (Quasi Homogeneous Evolution) Secondary (only for low mtallicities)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

   "source": [
    "One thing we need to be **very careful about** is **memory**.\n",
    "We don't want to fill up our RAM. If you do that in a jupyter notebook, the kernel will crash, saving you from having to reboot. \n",
    "\n",
    "If you fill up your RAM in a script without fail-safes, your computer will freeze and you will most likely have to reboot. \n",
    "\n",
    "So when creating new DataFrames like we just did, it's very important to **kill the previous, uncropped DataFrame to free that memory.**\n",
    "\n",
    "Before we kill it, let's see how much memory the binary models for z020 were taking up:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

   "source": [

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let's free that up:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",

     "data": {

    "gc.collect() \n",

    "# gc.collect() forces it to release memory allocations is doesn't need anymore. \n",
    "# not sure it works great in Jupyter notebooks, but if you run this in a script it should help. "

   "cell_type": "markdown",

   "source": [
    "For this particular case, we're going to select the following columns. Note that `filenames` is essential because it is basically the ID for each model (since there is pretty much 1 text file per modelled system). "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "metadata": {},

   "source": [
    "cols =['age','M1','log(L1)', 'log(T1)', 'log(R1)',\n",
    "       'M2','log(L2)', 'log(T2)', 'log(R2)',\n",
    "       'P_bin','log(a)', 'f435w','f555w', 'f814w', 'filenames']"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Now we replace our DataFrame by one that contains only the columns we care about\n",
    "only_binaries=only_binaries[cols].reset_index()"

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",

   "source": [
    "Okay so now we are working with a DataFrame of much more reasonable size 386,150 rows instead of 2.5 million. \n",
    "\n",
    "Now let's match our magnitudes.\n",
    "\n",
    "# Matching Magnitudes and Period\n",
    "\n",
    "Now we want to find which models can reproduce our observed magnitudes and potential period\n",
    "We use a conservative error=0.5, you can use your own."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#targets\n",
    "F435W=-7.33\n",
    "F435W_err=0.5 #arbitrary\n",
    "F814W=-8.46\n",
    "F814W_err=0.5 #arbitrary\n",
    "P=45\n",
    "P_err=15"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Before we apply conditions, we need to be careful, to the types of the columns we're going to rely on for the conditions. I know from trying this that the periods are not all floats - some numbers get messed up (not enough bits because the exponent is too big??) and look like this: -0.8122210+122 - which should be -0.8122210e+122. \n",
    "\n",
    "Anyways, these numbers are going to be plus infinities we don't want anyway. \n",
    "\n",
    "**Thankfully `pandas` has all the resources we need to elegantly take care of that!**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# This turns our P_bin column into floats, and if a cell cannot be turned into a float, a NaN is put in its place\n",
    "only_binaries['P_bin']=pd.to_numeric(only_binaries['P_bin'],errors='coerce')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Condition 1: Selects rows where the f435 column is within 0.5 mag or our target\n",
    "condition1 = (only_binaries.f435w<F435W+F435W_err) & (only_binaries.f435w>F435W-F435W_err)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Condition 2: Selects rows where the f814 column is within 0.5 mag or our target\n",
    "condition2 = (only_binaries.f814w<F814W+F814W_err) & (only_binaries.f814w>F814W-F814W_err)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Condition3: Select the period \n",
    "condition3 = (only_binaries.P_bin*365.25<P+P_err) & (only_binaries.P_bin*365.25>P-P_err)\n",
    "\n",
    "# We need ALL conditions to be met for a row to be selected\n",
    "mag_match=only_binaries[condition1 & condition2 & condition3]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Something to keep in mind is that **a star can stay within our magnitude targets for a while and so give multiple hits (rows)**. What we want is a list of _**unique**_ models that satisfy our query at some point in their lifetime. \n",
    "\n",
    "Thankfully, it's very easy in `pandas`:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "matching_model_list=mag_match.filenames.unique().tolist()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "'There are 264 matching models'"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 17,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "f\"There are {len(matching_model_list)} matching models\""
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now that we have a list of models that match, we need to retrieve their whole stellar evolution journey, not just the one that matches our magnitudes (otherwise our HR Diagram would look kinda weird). \n",
    "\n",
    "Let's make a new DataFrame:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# If this syntax seems odd, you might want to check out the following links:\n",
    "# https://python-3-patterns-idioms-test.readthedocs.io/en/latest/Comprehensions.html\n",
    "# https://chrisalbon.com/python/data_wrangling/pandas_selecting_rows_on_conditions/\n",
    "\n",
    "model_match_df=only_binaries[[True if model in matching_model_list \n",
    "                                 else False \n",
    "                                 for model in only_binaries.filenames]]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "769"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 19,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# And we get rid of stuff we don't need\n",
    "del only_binaries\n",
    "gc.collect() "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Plotting Evolutionary Tracks\n",
    "\n",
    "Now that we have the models we care about, let's have a look at where they lie on an HR Diagram and what kind of lifestyle they have. \n",
    "\n",
    "As any task implemented in python there are many ways you could do this, here is mine:\n",
    "* 1) First we iterate over each model ID (filename) and record the evolution of its Temperature, Luminosity, and Magnitudes in respective lists. \n",
    "* 2) We'll then collate these lists into a list of lists for each property (i.e. one list for temperature evolutions, one list for luminosity evolutions, etc..)\n",
    "* 3) We can then iterate over the length of our Lists of lists and plot them accordingly. \n",
    "\n",
    "Note you could combine step 3 with step 2 but I'd rather have the main lists saved so I can re-use them if I want."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Initiate Main Lists\n",
    "logT_list=[]\n",
    "logL_list=[]\n",
    "f435w_list=[]\n",
    "f814w_list=[]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Iterate over each model\n",
    "for model in matching_model_list:\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Data Frame containing solely the evolution of this one model\n",
    "    model_df = model_match_df[model_match_df.filenames==model]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Putting the T, L and mag ecolution in temp lists\n",
    "    logT, logL, f435w, f814w = model_df['log(T1)'].values, model_df['log(L1)'].values, model_df.f435w.values, model_df.f814w.values\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Appending these temp lists to our Master Lists. \n",
    "    logT_list.append(logT)\n",
    "    logL_list.append(logL)\n",
    "    f435w_list.append(f435w)\n",
    "    f814w_list.append(f814w)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Evolutionary Tracks\\nz020, M1>6, within 0.5 mag of target\\nwith P between 30 and 60 days')"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 21,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1500x1650 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "### And now we plot!\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(10,11))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Iterating over the length of our Master Lists (they all have the same length)\n",
    "for i in range(len(logT_list)):\n",
    "    # This is just easier later when we apply a mask\n",
    "    logT_i, logL_i = logT_list[i], logL_list[i]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Plot L Vs T\n",
    "    plt.plot(logT_i, logL_i, alpha=0.1, c='k', lw=1)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # We are also plotting where in the stellar evolution, our tracks produce the desired magnitudes\n",
    "    # These are the same conditions we had earlier \n",
    "    condition1 = (f435w_list[i]<F435W+F435W_err) & (f435w_list[i]>F435W-F435W_err)\n",
    "    condition2 = (f814w_list[i]<F814W+F814W_err) & (f814w_list[i]>F814W-F814W_err)\n",
    "    # Our mask is a combination of those two conditions\n",
    "    mask=condition1 & condition2\n",
    "    # We use a scatter plot to show the masked L and T combinations \n",
    "    plt.scatter(logT_i[mask], logL_i[mask], zorder=1000, c='coral', alpha=0.3)\n",
    "    \n",
    "# Just some limits - also flips the Temperature axis, to make this an HRD\n",
    "plt.xlim([5.5, 3.5])\n",
    "plt.ylim([3,6])\n",
    "\n",
    "#Labels\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Log(L)')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Log(T)')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.title('Evolutionary Tracks\\nz020, M1>6, within 0.5 mag of target\\nwith P between 30 and 60 days')"
   ]
  },
